91
00:06:15,880 --> 00:06:19,940
Obara! Welcome.

92
00:06:19,940 --> 00:06:22,140
I look forward to working with you.

93
00:06:24,800 --> 00:06:27,900
Excuse me. This is Onsen Manju from Hakone.
<i>(T/N: Steamed buns)</i>

94
00:06:27,900 --> 00:06:29,280
Please have some.

95
00:06:29,280 --> 00:06:31,900
The clothes you're wearing are the same as those
<i>["The River No One Crosses" by Sherri Winston]</i>

96
00:06:31,900 --> 00:06:36,140
worn by the colonel when he first met his mother-in-law,

97
00:06:36,140 --> 00:06:40,890
in the book "The River No One Crosses," by highly-acclaimed author, Sherri Winston.

98
00:06:42,260 --> 00:06:46,650
"At that moment, like the redness of the flare of the brilliant, shining sun,

99
00:06:46,650 --> 00:06:48,700
being glazed green in the blink of an eye..."

100
00:06:48,700 --> 00:06:53,120
<i>Will I be able to do this?</i>

101
00:06:53,120 --> 00:06:56,480
"That cannot be compared to the sweet glow

102
00:06:56,480 --> 00:06:59,560
of the white flowers blooming on the cuffs

103
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:03,500
of the alluring black dress that she was wearing."

104
00:07:04,080 --> 00:07:07,550
As quoted in the introduction. I'm sure you know of it?

105
00:07:07,550 --> 00:07:09,360
No, I don't.

106
00:07:11,130 --> 00:07:13,710
Chief Komatsubara! Are you all right?

107
00:07:13,710 --> 00:07:16,500
I'm fine, I'm fine. This happens often, so...

108
00:07:16,500 --> 00:07:20,230
- Is that so?
- I have something important to tell you. Come over here.

109
00:07:20,230 --> 00:07:21,700
Okay.

110
00:07:21,700 --> 00:07:25,040
Ren Minazuki, do you know him?

111
00:07:25,040 --> 00:07:28,410
He's a very popular romance novelist among youngsters, right?

112
00:07:28,410 --> 00:07:31,810
That's right. He's our best-selling author.

113
00:07:31,810 --> 00:07:36,010
One by one, his novels become best-sellers and get adapted into movies, which become blockbusters too.

114
00:07:36,010 --> 00:07:38,570
Even now, he is a romance celebrity.

115
00:07:38,570 --> 00:07:42,980
And that Ren Minazuki specifically requested for you to be his manager.

116
00:07:42,980 --> 00:07:45,340
- What?
- Where do you know each other from?

117
00:07:46,030 --> 00:07:49,620
Well, I don't think we have ever met.

118
00:07:49,620 --> 00:07:51,250
Wait, wait, wait...

119
00:07:51,250 --> 00:07:54,210
Forget about it. In any case, go and pay him a visit now.

120
00:07:54,210 --> 00:07:56,530
His current manager is also with him now.
<i>[M.R Office]</i>

121
00:07:56,530 --> 00:07:58,390
Excuse me.

122
00:07:58,950 --> 00:08:02,050
<i>For how many years have you been at this job?</i>

123
00:08:02,050 --> 00:08:04,550
I heard that you like red wine, so...

124
00:08:04,550 --> 00:08:08,270
I only drink red Bourgogne.

125
00:08:08,270 --> 00:08:11,600
- You're such a useless old man.
- I am sorry!

126
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:13,600
Forget it.

127
00:08:13,600 --> 00:08:16,780
Here. I've added my comments.

128
00:08:16,780 --> 00:08:19,240
Thank you very much!

129
00:08:22,120 --> 00:08:25,120
The fact that you can't catch my script

130
00:08:25,120 --> 00:08:27,630
shows your failure as a manager.

131
00:08:29,040 --> 00:08:30,660
Are you all right?

132
00:08:30,660 --> 00:08:32,580
I'm fine, I'm fine. I'm f-fine.

133
00:08:32,580 --> 00:08:34,420
Thank you very much!

134
00:08:41,770 --> 00:08:45,260
"You're horrible" is written all over your face.

135
00:08:46,740 --> 00:08:49,730
I've always wanted to try doing this for once.

136
00:08:50,360 --> 00:08:54,340
Old man, I'll email it over to you.

137
00:08:55,070 --> 00:08:58,190
But you're fired... as manager.

138
00:08:59,180 --> 00:09:03,860
By the way, do you really not remember me?

139
00:09:03,860 --> 00:09:06,070
<i>Saki Obara.</i>

140
00:09:07,240 --> 00:09:10,690
<i>So do you believe in love?</i>

141
00:09:10,690 --> 00:09:12,460
You're from that time...

142
00:09:12,460 --> 00:09:15,840
Why did you specifically request for me to be your manager?

143
00:09:16,890 --> 00:09:18,920
Your face.

144
00:09:20,410 --> 00:09:24,890
The next time you come, bring a red Bourgogne Vintage Romanee Richbourg

145
00:09:24,890 --> 00:09:26,680
and unsweetened jelly beans.

146
00:09:26,680 --> 00:09:30,910
- Huh?
- And also... prepare some red spider lilies.

147
00:09:30,910 --> 00:09:32,480
Red spider lilies?

148
00:09:32,480 --> 00:09:36,760
- What are red spider lilies...
- If it's too much for you, I'll swap you out as my manager.

149
00:09:36,760 --> 00:09:39,680
One more thing. As and when required,

150
00:09:39,680 --> 00:09:43,180
you must always answer my call.

151
00:09:43,180 --> 00:09:45,340
What is this man?

152
00:09:45,340 --> 00:09:47,710
A romance celebrity?

153
00:09:47,710 --> 00:09:49,890
Which part of it?

154
00:09:55,060 --> 00:09:57,370
You've been feeling down since this morning.

155
00:09:57,370 --> 00:09:59,380
Not at all!

156
00:10:01,570 --> 00:10:04,050
Did you quarrel with your wife?

157
00:10:04,050 --> 00:10:06,600
What? No.

158
00:10:06,600 --> 00:10:08,180
Master Sergeant Obara!

159
00:10:08,180 --> 00:10:11,660
We were discussing our plans for the holidays.

160
00:10:11,660 --> 00:10:15,350
- What is it?
- It's about our visit to your house.

161
00:10:15,350 --> 00:10:18,210
Your wife's mother is throwing a party, right?

162
00:10:18,210 --> 00:10:19,760
What?

163
00:10:19,760 --> 00:10:22,140
- What is this about?
- What do you mean by this?

164
00:10:22,140 --> 00:10:25,420
How scary, the both of you!

165
00:10:25,420 --> 00:10:26,640
I heard from Tani

166
00:10:26,640 --> 00:10:30,180
that you exchanged contacts with him at our wedding!

167
00:10:30,180 --> 00:10:31,770
That's right!

168
00:10:31,770 --> 00:10:33,770
Tani is really cute, isn't he?

169
00:10:33,770 --> 00:10:36,390
Mom, bear in mind your age difference.

170
00:10:36,390 --> 00:10:39,220
Wrong, wrong, you've got it all wrong.

171
00:10:39,220 --> 00:10:42,660
Tani said his girlfriend is a fan of mine.

172
00:10:42,660 --> 00:10:45,070
I merely sent him my autographed book.

173
00:10:45,070 --> 00:10:49,860
What? Why are you throwing your birthday party at my place?

174
00:10:49,860 --> 00:10:51,470
I can throw it here if I want to, can't I?

175
00:10:51,470 --> 00:10:54,360
After all, if I do it here,

176
00:10:54,360 --> 00:10:56,770
that man will also come, won't he?

177
00:10:56,770 --> 00:10:58,410
Do you mean Dad?

178
00:10:58,410 --> 00:11:02,780
She may have returned home, but they are both sleeping in separate rooms.

179
00:11:04,680 --> 00:11:08,020
<i>Welcome home!</i>

180
00:11:08,020 --> 00:11:09,990
<i>Azusa, good job getting here!</i>

181
00:11:09,990 --> 00:11:13,580
<i> Azusa and I will be staying here for the time being, if it's okay with you? </i>

182
00:11:13,580 --> 00:11:14,960
<i> Sure. </i>

183
00:11:14,960 --> 00:11:16,160
<i>Huh?</i>

184
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:18,410
<i>Dad, did you change your glasses?</i>

185
00:11:18,410 --> 00:11:20,830
<i>Yes. A makeover.
[Takeshi Mizuguchi]</i>

186
00:11:20,830 --> 00:11:22,540
<i> Mom, you wouldn't want to talk about that. </i>

187
00:11:22,540 --> 00:11:23,610
<i> Right. </i>

188
00:11:23,610 --> 00:11:24,840
<i>[Takeshi Mizuguchi]</i>

189
00:11:25,490 --> 00:11:29,660
<i> Midori, since you're back, shall we all eat out? </i>

190
00:11:29,660 --> 00:11:32,210
<i>I didn't come home because I wanted to.</i>

191
00:11:32,210 --> 00:11:34,560
<i>We should sleep in separate rooms.</i>

192
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:36,750
<i>Tell him that, Kaede.</i>

193
00:11:36,750 --> 00:11:37,930
<i> That's what she said.</i>

194
00:11:37,930 --> 00:11:39,470
<i> Midori... </i>

195
00:11:39,470 --> 00:11:42,950
<i>Please, feel free to stay over at your friend's place.</i>

196
00:11:42,950 --> 00:11:45,750
<i>Tell him that, Kaede, Azusa!</i>

197
00:11:45,750 --> 00:11:47,280
<i>- That's what she said.
- That's what she said. </i>

198
00:11:47,280 --> 00:11:49,670
<i>Midori!</i>

199
00:11:49,670 --> 00:11:52,560
Do you plan to not talk to him directly, Mom?

200
00:11:52,560 --> 00:11:55,540
Well, I don't want to.

201
00:11:55,540 --> 00:11:57,100
Azusa, time for your bath.

202
00:11:57,100 --> 00:11:59,120
Okay.

203
00:11:59,120 --> 00:12:00,800
So where is Dad?

204
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:03,060
He said he was going to his friend's place.

205
00:12:03,060 --> 00:12:07,450
Just what exactly is Dad doing this time?
<i>[Obara]</i>

206
00:12:07,450 --> 00:12:11,390
Midori was beautiful when she was young.

207
00:12:12,100 --> 00:12:14,760
Do you know what's a car companion?

208
00:12:14,760 --> 00:12:15,850
No.

209
00:12:15,850 --> 00:12:19,110
It refers to those beautiful girls standing in front of sports cars.

210
00:12:19,110 --> 00:12:20,840
I see.

211
00:12:20,840 --> 00:12:22,580
Driving them down from Harumi

212
00:12:22,580 --> 00:12:27,120
is a mark of status for men like us working in the advertising agency.

213
00:12:27,120 --> 00:12:29,210
Midori was popular.

214
00:12:29,210 --> 00:12:34,080
By the way, how did you and your wife fall in love, Obara?

215
00:12:34,080 --> 00:12:36,000
We were match-made.

216
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:38,920
You sure looked like it!

217
00:12:38,920 --> 00:12:41,300
Of course, they were beautiful when young,

218
00:12:41,300 --> 00:12:42,940
but at this kind of age,

219
00:12:42,940 --> 00:12:46,370
it's a matter of whether anybody desires them as women.

220
00:12:46,370 --> 00:12:48,760
- Agreed.
- They don't have anywhere to go, right?

221
00:12:48,760 --> 00:12:51,760
- Agreed.
- In the end, they have no choice but to return home.

222
00:12:51,760 --> 00:12:52,880
Agreed!

223
00:12:52,880 --> 00:12:55,870
Cheers!

224
00:12:55,870 --> 00:12:58,060
So that's why I beg of you.

225
00:12:58,060 --> 00:13:03,620
Please let me throw my birthday party at your place!

226
00:13:03,620 --> 00:13:06,010
This will be the last time for this year.

227
00:13:06,010 --> 00:13:07,760
The last time?

228
00:13:09,450 --> 00:13:13,210
I used to celebrate with the whole family every year.

229
00:13:13,210 --> 00:13:18,010
If I divorce, that will not happen ever again.

230
00:13:19,900 --> 00:13:23,390
Please? That's why I beg of you!

231
00:13:23,390 --> 00:13:26,790
I already notified everybody.

232
00:13:26,790 --> 00:13:28,900
What? Who?

233
00:13:28,900 --> 00:13:30,690
There are Koichi's subordinates,

234
00:13:30,690 --> 00:13:34,340
my model friends from MiMaJo, and my editor, Tachikawa.

235
00:13:34,340 --> 00:13:35,690
And there's Takaya too.

236
00:13:35,690 --> 00:13:39,030
What? Why did you invite him without my consent?

237
00:13:39,030 --> 00:13:40,670
Not long ago,

238
00:13:40,670 --> 00:13:43,860
I accidentally caused him some trouble, so this is my way of apologizing to him.

239
00:13:43,860 --> 00:13:49,200
Furthermore, you were with Takaya for five years after all.

240
00:13:49,200 --> 00:13:51,960
You can still continue to be friends, can't you?

241
00:13:51,960 --> 00:13:54,490
Stop it, Mom!

242
00:13:57,280 --> 00:13:59,460
Let's go home, Koichi.

243
00:14:00,480 --> 00:14:02,910
Please excuse us.

244
00:14:02,910 --> 00:14:04,570
I just can't believe it.

245
00:14:04,570 --> 00:14:06,990
What is she thinking?

246
00:14:08,020 --> 00:14:10,210
Are you angry, Koichi?

247
00:14:10,210 --> 00:14:11,570
No, I'm not.

248
00:14:12,430 --> 00:14:13,980
It's making you feel awful, right?

249
00:14:13,980 --> 00:14:17,750
Sorry that you have to keep hearing things about my ex.

250
00:14:17,750 --> 00:14:19,420
I'm fine with it.

251
00:14:19,420 --> 00:14:22,260
You may not mind it,

252
00:14:22,260 --> 00:14:24,210
but I do.

253
00:14:24,210 --> 00:14:27,150
We are still husband and wife, after all.

254
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:38,990
I don't have my mobile. I think I left it behind.

255
00:14:38,990 --> 00:14:41,850
Go ahead and get into the car first.

256
00:14:47,620 --> 00:14:50,800
What is it? Did you forget something?

257
00:14:50,800 --> 00:14:52,610
Well...

258
00:14:53,750 --> 00:14:55,730
Could you tell me more

259
00:14:55,730 --> 00:14:58,290
about Aoyama?

260
00:14:58,290 --> 00:15:02,820
- What?
- What do you think about Saki and him?

261
00:15:02,820 --> 00:15:04,810
Well...

262
00:15:04,810 --> 00:15:06,550
You don't need to bother about my feelings!

263
00:15:06,550 --> 00:15:08,900
I need to know the truth.

264
00:15:13,980 --> 00:15:17,840
They were very suited for each other.

265
00:15:17,840 --> 00:15:21,450
Takaya is a fine young man, and he's kind.

266
00:15:21,450 --> 00:15:23,650
He knows everything about Saki.

267
00:15:23,650 --> 00:15:25,880
They have similar interests and opinions,

268
00:15:25,880 --> 00:15:29,380
it's a wonder why they didn't get married.

269
00:15:30,100 --> 00:15:35,700
Of course, I'm happy that you and Saki got married!

270
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:06,380
<i>[This feeling, fleeting, heartrending.]</i>

271
00:16:33,240 --> 00:16:38,130
This is the Domaine de la Romanee Richbourge Vintage Bourgogne.

272
00:16:38,130 --> 00:16:42,430
Produced in 1990, it is touted as a phantom commodity,

273
00:16:42,430 --> 00:16:47,290
and these are the unsweetened jelly beans.

274
00:16:47,290 --> 00:16:49,730
As for the red spider lilies,

275
00:16:49,730 --> 00:16:52,720
I couldn't find them at any florist all over Tokyo,

276
00:16:52,720 --> 00:16:55,330
so I used my connections in the fashion industry

277
00:16:55,330 --> 00:17:00,670
to locate a farmer in Hokkaido, who cultivates potted plants in a greenhouse as his hobby,

278
00:17:00,670 --> 00:17:02,990
and got my hands on them just moments ago.

279
00:17:02,990 --> 00:17:05,790
Oh? I'm impressed.

280
00:17:06,480 --> 00:17:08,480
You're doing your job properly.

281
00:17:08,480 --> 00:17:10,600
Huh?

282
00:17:10,600 --> 00:17:12,950
I thought you only got by using your looks.

283
00:17:12,950 --> 00:17:15,830
I shall take that as a compliment.

284
00:17:17,190 --> 00:17:19,180
Sit down!

285
00:17:19,180 --> 00:17:21,350
Thank you.

286
00:17:21,350 --> 00:17:23,650
About the novel that I'm currently working on...

287
00:17:23,650 --> 00:17:25,200
Yes.

288
00:17:25,200 --> 00:17:27,730
It's about a man who appeared in a newlywed couple's house

289
00:17:27,730 --> 00:17:29,630
and turns out to be the wife's ex-boyfriend.

290
00:17:29,630 --> 00:17:31,610
What?

291
00:17:31,610 --> 00:17:34,900
It's nothing. Please continue.

292
00:17:35,900 --> 00:17:40,180
The husband was shocked to find out about the ex-boyfriend's existence.

293
00:17:40,830 --> 00:17:42,370
Would it be childish if he's angry?

294
00:17:42,370 --> 00:17:44,050
It's better if he's angry!

295
00:17:44,050 --> 00:17:46,880
Oh? That's rather direct. Why so?

296
00:17:46,880 --> 00:17:48,100
Well...

297
00:17:48,100 --> 00:17:50,810
It's about my friend.

298
00:17:50,810 --> 00:17:53,340
Her ex-boyfriend appeared

299
00:17:53,340 --> 00:17:55,590
and she wanted to explain it to her husband,

300
00:17:55,590 --> 00:17:58,880
but he did not mind one bit.

301
00:17:58,880 --> 00:18:01,620
Although he did not mind,

302
00:18:01,620 --> 00:18:03,620
she felt uncomfortable about it.

303
00:18:03,620 --> 00:18:07,010
In fact, it annoyed her.

304
00:18:07,820 --> 00:18:10,740
That's because she loves him, doesn't she?

305
00:18:10,740 --> 00:18:12,870
She loves him, that's why she feels uncomfortable.

306
00:18:12,870 --> 00:18:15,000
She doesn't want to be misunderstood.

307
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,300
She wants him to feel jealous.

308
00:18:19,710 --> 00:18:22,850
Such love for your husband.

309
00:18:22,850 --> 00:18:24,660
No, I don't mean it that way...

310
00:18:24,660 --> 00:18:26,710
Your friend, I mean.

311
00:18:35,640 --> 00:18:38,970
<i>Am I in love with him?</i>

312
00:18:42,020 --> 00:18:45,050
<i>Are we still in time</i>

313
00:18:45,770 --> 00:18:48,710
<i>to salvage the situation?</i>

314
00:18:52,330 --> 00:18:53,740
<i>If I</i>

315
00:18:53,740 --> 00:18:58,580
<i>tell him that I want us to start over...</i>

316
00:18:58,580 --> 00:19:00,090
<i>If I</i>

317
00:19:00,820 --> 00:19:03,050
<i>tell him that...</i>

318
00:19:03,050 --> 00:19:05,350
- I'm home!
- Yes, I have received it.

319
00:19:05,350 --> 00:19:06,780
Yes.

320
00:19:06,780 --> 00:19:09,090
We will take a look at it.

321
00:19:09,090 --> 00:19:11,320
All right, goodbye.

322
00:19:12,330 --> 00:19:15,730
That was the realtor. They have conducted a valuation of our house.

323
00:19:15,730 --> 00:19:17,500
If we divorce,

324
00:19:17,500 --> 00:19:20,730
we'll need to consider the possibility of selling it.
<i>[Property Valuation Report]</i>

325
00:19:21,630 --> 00:19:24,920
This is the house you took a liking to and personally renovated.

326
00:19:24,920 --> 00:19:28,300
I don't mind if you plan on continuing to live here by yourself.

327
00:19:29,620 --> 00:19:31,820
This house is too big.

328
00:19:31,820 --> 00:19:34,060
I'm unable to repay the loan on my own anyway.

329
00:19:34,060 --> 00:19:36,220
I see.

330
00:19:36,220 --> 00:19:41,210
In that case, first off, let's look for a buyer who will purchase it.

331
00:19:41,920 --> 00:19:45,510
Also, I just received this.

332
00:19:47,580 --> 00:19:49,610
<i>[Application for Divorce]</i>

333
00:19:50,660 --> 00:19:52,670
<i>[Name: Koichi Obara]</i>

334
00:19:53,180 --> 00:19:54,800
Why?

335
00:19:57,380 --> 00:19:58,900
Well...

336
00:19:58,900 --> 00:20:02,070
This is somehow all too sudden.

337
00:20:02,940 --> 00:20:05,390
We are, after all,

338
00:20:06,530 --> 00:20:10,640
getting a... divorce, aren't we?

339
00:20:10,640 --> 00:20:12,790
That's right, but...

340
00:20:12,790 --> 00:20:15,390
Then we'll need to start making arrangements.

341
00:20:34,800 --> 00:20:39,030
I've also given it a lot of thought.

342
00:20:39,030 --> 00:20:41,800
Why don't we let your mom throw her birthday party here?

343
00:20:41,800 --> 00:20:43,190
What? Why?

344
00:20:43,190 --> 00:20:48,400
This will be the first and last time I can celebrate your mom's birthday as part of your family.

345
00:20:48,400 --> 00:20:54,410
Furthermore, if your parents are really getting a divorce,

346
00:20:54,410 --> 00:21:00,100
all the more, we should all gather together and celebrate.

347
00:21:02,900 --> 00:21:07,900
Your family... holds home parties every year, right?

348
00:21:12,290 --> 00:21:15,010
We always have our own dinners separately

349
00:21:15,010 --> 00:21:18,520
at our own convenience,

350
00:21:18,520 --> 00:21:20,710
but when it comes to Mom's birthday,

351
00:21:20,710 --> 00:21:24,210
we all agreed we'd gather together to celebrate it.
<i>â™ª Happy Birthday to you â™ª</i>

352
00:21:24,210 --> 00:21:26,730
Dad would come home early that day,
<i>â™ª Happy Birthday, dear Midori â™ª</i>

353
00:21:26,730 --> 00:21:31,140
and buy Mom a cake and a flower bouquet.
<i>â™ª Happy Birthday to you â™ª</i>

354
00:21:33,610 --> 00:21:38,180
And among the red roses in the bouquet he bought for her,

355
00:21:38,180 --> 00:21:42,520
there would be white roses, the number which represents the number of years they have been married.

356
00:21:43,540 --> 00:21:45,790
Makes you feel fuzzy inside, don't you think?

357
00:21:45,790 --> 00:21:47,580
It's a good memory to have.

358
00:21:47,580 --> 00:21:49,330
Really?

359
00:21:49,330 --> 00:21:51,080
It's wonderful.

360
00:21:51,950 --> 00:21:55,340
My family doesn't have such a practice.

361
00:22:03,590 --> 00:22:05,530
Koichi...

362
00:22:05,530 --> 00:22:06,810
You and I...

363
00:22:20,570 --> 00:22:22,400
Koichi...

364
00:22:23,570 --> 00:22:28,970
Thank you for thinking about my family.

365
00:22:32,120 --> 00:22:33,780
It's nothing.

366
00:22:36,310 --> 00:22:39,610
We'll have to start preparing if we're going to have a party.

367
00:22:40,510 --> 00:22:42,720
You're right.

368
00:22:43,650 --> 00:22:46,600
For a start, let's hang up the curtains we bought, shall we?

369
00:22:46,600 --> 00:22:49,430
Not yet. Not this one!

370
00:22:49,430 --> 00:22:51,960
This doesn't do?

371
00:22:52,550 --> 00:22:55,220
Sorry about that.

372
00:22:59,190 --> 00:23:02,590
- After Mom's birthday party...
- Yeah?

373
00:23:02,590 --> 00:23:07,090
Shall we break the news to the relevant people? Regarding our divorce.

374
00:23:08,830 --> 00:23:10,470
Let's do that.

375
00:23:12,220 --> 00:23:14,590
I'll let my dad know.

376
00:23:14,590 --> 00:23:17,160
If my parents are able to make up with each other,

377
00:23:17,160 --> 00:23:20,980
it'll be easier to break the news of our divorce to them.

378
00:23:33,720 --> 00:23:36,950
Midori and the girls have gone shopping.

379
00:23:36,950 --> 00:23:40,590
I'm here to tell you something, Dad.

380
00:23:40,590 --> 00:23:42,800
You know it's Mom's birthday tomorrow, right?

381
00:23:42,800 --> 00:23:44,000
Right.

382
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:47,530
Koichi suggested that we should celebrate it at our place.

383
00:23:47,530 --> 00:23:50,120
Can you come too, Dad?

384
00:23:50,120 --> 00:23:52,980
What did Midori say?

385
00:23:52,980 --> 00:23:56,910
She didn't plan on inviting me anyway, that's why she wanted to hold the party there, right?

386
00:23:56,910 --> 00:23:59,670
In that case, there's no point in me going.

387
00:23:59,670 --> 00:24:02,150
Then do you plan on breaking up like this?

388
00:24:02,150 --> 00:24:06,330
Of course not! Why would we do that?

389
00:24:07,810 --> 00:24:12,320
Mom said... that she will make this her last birthday party.

390
00:24:12,320 --> 00:24:16,310
I have a feeling that this time, it's different from her usual whims.

391
00:24:16,310 --> 00:24:18,770
Midori is just making a mountain out of a molehill!

392
00:24:18,770 --> 00:24:21,880
She'll eventually come round and say, "Let's do it again next year."

393
00:24:21,880 --> 00:24:23,340
You're so confident about it.

394
00:24:23,340 --> 00:24:25,920
We've been together for 35 years.

395
00:24:25,920 --> 00:24:29,100
We're different from those newlyweds who just got married.

396
00:24:29,100 --> 00:24:30,490
It's all right.

397
00:24:30,490 --> 00:24:33,620
Not to worry, I said.

398
00:24:33,620 --> 00:24:37,300
Even if we think, "It's all right, we still have time."

399
00:24:37,300 --> 00:24:41,100
Before we know it, we won't be able to turn back the clock.

400
00:24:41,100 --> 00:24:44,120
If that happens, it will be too late!

401
00:24:46,580 --> 00:24:48,410
Dad!

402
00:24:48,410 --> 00:24:52,190
Oh, right! Do you want to take home some dried mullet roe as a souvenir?

403
00:24:52,190 --> 00:24:55,140
They're really good!

404
00:24:56,720 --> 00:24:58,790
- One, two!
- One, two!

405
00:25:02,080 --> 00:25:03,810
It's done.

406
00:25:16,540 --> 00:25:20,090
Miss Saki, you've got the wrong helium.

407
00:26:16,280 --> 00:26:18,390
It's so bright.

408
00:26:22,160 --> 00:26:25,310
Look, Koichi!

409
00:26:29,840 --> 00:26:31,560
I'm fine.

410
00:26:34,120 --> 00:26:36,090
It's beautiful.

411
00:26:37,680 --> 00:26:39,170
Yes, it is.

412
00:26:39,170 --> 00:26:41,980
It's beautiful without the curtains too.

413
00:26:45,240 --> 00:26:47,260
You're right.

414
00:26:50,530 --> 00:26:52,900
Thank you for inviting us to today's party!

415
00:26:52,900 --> 00:26:54,290
- Excuse us!
- Excuse us!

416
00:26:54,290 --> 00:26:57,020
A stand-up buffet means you're not supposed to sit-Â 

417
00:26:57,020 --> 00:26:59,550
Hi, Tani!

418
00:26:59,550 --> 00:27:02,350
Welcome, all of you!

419
00:27:02,350 --> 00:27:05,220
These models here are my friends.

420
00:27:05,220 --> 00:27:06,530
- Nice to meet you!
- Nice to meet you!

421
00:27:06,530 --> 00:27:09,000
What's this? Are we in a palace?

422
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:11,400
- Feels like we're in the Dragon King Palace!
- We put this here.

423
00:27:11,400 --> 00:27:14,020
Looking forward to it!

424
00:27:17,850 --> 00:27:21,150
- Hello.
- Hello.

425
00:27:22,420 --> 00:27:25,470
I'm sorry for what happened the other day.

426
00:27:26,640 --> 00:27:28,930
No problem about it.

427
00:27:28,930 --> 00:27:31,550
Please enjoy yourself.

428
00:27:34,210 --> 00:27:35,580
Midori!

429
00:27:35,580 --> 00:27:36,900
Happy birthday to you!

430
00:27:36,900 --> 00:27:39,390
Oh, my! Thank you!

431
00:27:39,390 --> 00:27:41,090
Excuse me, ma'am.

432
00:27:41,090 --> 00:27:44,090
I've also brought some food.

433
00:27:44,090 --> 00:27:48,380
Though I don't think it's as delicious as those you prepared.

434
00:27:48,380 --> 00:27:50,320
These are mostly takeaways.

435
00:27:50,320 --> 00:27:53,740
That's right. The only dish Saki made is this potato salad.

436
00:27:53,740 --> 00:27:56,050
Since she was younger, she has never been good at cooking.

437
00:27:56,050 --> 00:27:57,480
Stop it, Sis.

438
00:27:57,480 --> 00:27:58,650
Is that so?

439
00:27:58,650 --> 00:28:00,080
Second Lieutenant Ichinose, you brought something?

440
00:28:00,080 --> 00:28:02,520
Yes! It's chikuzenni and oden.
<i> (T/N: Simmered chicken and vegetables)</i>

441
00:28:02,520 --> 00:28:05,590
That's nice of you. My mom often cooks them too.

442
00:28:05,590 --> 00:28:07,150
Oh, really?

443
00:28:08,380 --> 00:28:12,420
Chikuzenni and oden... Isn't she somehow showing her assertiveness over you?

444
00:28:12,420 --> 00:28:16,870
- Stop it.
- That's true. It's like saying, "I can make food like your mom does."

445
00:28:16,870 --> 00:28:21,530
Somehow, this feels like we're a newlywed couple.

446
00:28:23,760 --> 00:28:25,630
I'm kidding.

447
00:28:32,990 --> 00:28:35,780
Let's put our glasses together for Midori's birthday. Cheers!

448
00:28:35,780 --> 00:28:39,430
- Cheers!
- Cheers!

449
00:28:40,430 --> 00:28:42,200
I'm so happy!

450
00:28:42,200 --> 00:28:44,450
Have one.

451
00:28:45,750 --> 00:28:46,780
This is delish!

452
00:28:46,780 --> 00:28:49,550
This is the taste of being newly married!

453
00:29:01,930 --> 00:29:04,600
Can I help you?

454
00:29:04,600 --> 00:29:08,250
I'm sorry! I was wondering whom does this room this belongs to.

455
00:29:09,230 --> 00:29:11,700
What a wonderful home you have.

456
00:29:11,700 --> 00:29:14,680
The entrance, living room, and bedroom.

457
00:29:14,680 --> 00:29:16,300
They're all wonderful.

458
00:29:16,300 --> 00:29:18,650
Thank you very much.

459
00:29:20,750 --> 00:29:23,940
You're an editor for a fashion magazine, right?

460
00:29:23,940 --> 00:29:25,880
It feels like

461
00:29:25,880 --> 00:29:29,010
we live in different worlds.

462
00:29:29,010 --> 00:29:31,060
Don't think of it that way.

463
00:29:31,060 --> 00:29:32,550
We...

464
00:29:33,750 --> 00:29:37,100
often move together as a team.

465
00:29:37,100 --> 00:29:40,890
One person's mistake can cost the lives of the entire team.

466
00:29:40,890 --> 00:29:42,360
I'm not exaggerating,

467
00:29:42,360 --> 00:29:45,370
but we risk our lives everyday.

468
00:29:45,370 --> 00:29:50,450
That's why... we always have to be in our best forms.

469
00:29:50,450 --> 00:29:54,520
Are you... fully devoting your all...

470
00:29:54,520 --> 00:29:57,030
for Master Sergeant Obara?

471
00:29:59,190 --> 00:30:02,210
I'm sorry, I've said too much.

472
00:30:02,210 --> 00:30:06,120
He is, after all, my superior. That's why I'm worried about him.

473
00:30:07,020 --> 00:30:08,210
It's all right.

474
00:30:08,210 --> 00:30:10,130
Please excuse me.

475
00:30:22,550 --> 00:30:24,020
<i>[Stay-Life-Home Realtor]</i>

476
00:30:27,290 --> 00:30:29,180
This is Obara.

477
00:30:30,440 --> 00:30:31,980
Yes.

478
00:30:37,760 --> 00:30:40,100
Is this regarding the valuation previously?

479
00:30:44,510 --> 00:30:48,810
I'm sorry, I'll revise it afterward. Bye.

480
00:30:50,400 --> 00:30:52,220
Sorry, I just let myself into the veranda.

481
00:30:52,220 --> 00:30:53,930
It's all right.

482
00:30:58,690 --> 00:31:00,940
I'm sorry for what happened the other day.

483
00:31:00,940 --> 00:31:02,890
I wasn't aware...

484
00:31:03,510 --> 00:31:05,980
that you were Saki's husband.

485
00:31:05,980 --> 00:31:07,930
No worries about that.

486
00:31:07,930 --> 00:31:11,100
You and I... both didn't know.

487
00:31:13,430 --> 00:31:15,880
It's unbelievable.

488
00:31:15,880 --> 00:31:19,720
If I were in your shoes, I wouldn't be able to let it go so easily.

489
00:31:19,720 --> 00:31:20,910
It's nothing.

490
00:31:20,910 --> 00:31:23,020
I feel embarrassed for saying she married you out of spite.

491
00:31:23,020 --> 00:31:24,500
S-S-Spite?

492
00:31:25,550 --> 00:31:28,440
I guess I shouldn't have come, after all.

493
00:31:29,050 --> 00:31:31,390
It feels a little terrible

494
00:31:31,390 --> 00:31:33,740
to see how blissful Saki looks.

495
00:31:35,730 --> 00:31:38,930
You mean...

496
00:31:40,890 --> 00:31:43,110
you haven't gotten over...

497
00:31:43,110 --> 00:31:46,620
I'm sorry! What am I saying?

498
00:31:46,620 --> 00:31:48,510
Please forget about it.

499
00:31:59,380 --> 00:32:01,640
What were you both talking about?

500
00:32:05,960 --> 00:32:07,560
Nothing much.

501
00:32:09,280 --> 00:32:11,090
Are you angry?

502
00:32:13,260 --> 00:32:15,170
No.

503
00:32:27,830 --> 00:32:30,740
Your dishes were delicious.

504
00:32:30,740 --> 00:32:32,580
Thank you very much.

505
00:32:32,580 --> 00:32:35,180
You love Koichi, right?

506
00:32:37,030 --> 00:32:38,290
What are you talking about?

507
00:32:38,290 --> 00:32:40,130
I know very well

508
00:32:40,130 --> 00:32:42,300
the pain of a love

509
00:32:42,300 --> 00:32:44,060
that is unreciprocated.

510
00:32:49,540 --> 00:32:52,020
But the law is terrifying.

511
00:32:52,020 --> 00:32:54,090
In the case of an affair,

512
00:32:54,090 --> 00:32:56,930
there's a risk that the wife may demand compensation from the husband.

513
00:32:56,930 --> 00:32:58,880
It's better to give up.

514
00:33:02,060 --> 00:33:03,810
